## Modular Constraint on Outer Digits
For a 4-digit number $n = abcd$, if $n+r(n)=A^2$, then $1001(a+d) + 110(b+c) = A^2$.
This implies $A$ is a multiple of 11, say $A=11j$.
Then $121j^2 = 1001(a+d) + 110(b+c)$.
Dividing by 11: $11j^2 = 91(a+d) + 10(b+c)$.
Modulo 10: $j^2 \equiv a+d \pmod{10}$.
So $a+d$ must be a quadratic residue mod 10.
</read_from_notebook>
