## Non-trivial Solutions to $n \pm r(n)$ being squares
The only 2-digit non-trivial solution is $n=65$.
$n=65, r(n)=56$.
$n-r(n) = 9 = 3^2$.
$n+r(n) = 121 = 11^2$.

There are no 3-digit or 4-digit non-trivial solutions.
3-digit numbers force $n$ to be a palindrome if $n-r(n)$ is a square.
4-digit numbers have modular constraints that make $n+r(n)$ not a square.

There are infinitely many trivial solutions where $n$ is a palindrome and $n=2k^2$.
Example: $n=242$.
$n=242, r(n)=242$.
$n-r(n) = 0 = 0^2$.
$n+r(n) = 484 = 22^2$.

