2 \equiv 1 + 90 = 91 \pmod{100}$.
But 91 is not a quadratic residue modulo 100. The last two digits of a square can only be 00, 01, 04, 09, 16, 21, 24, 25, 29, 36, 41, 44, 49, 56, 61, 64, 69, 76, 81, 84, 89, 96. 91 is not on the list.
So $n + r(n)$ could never be a square for that specific set of outer digits, regardless of $c$.

This is powerful. The inner digit $c$ doesn't even matter for the modulo 100 constraint. The sum modulo 100 is determined entirely by the outer two pairs of digits. And if that residue isn't a square mod 100, the whole thing fails.

